[normal]Written Evidence submitted by the [bold]Newcastle University [bold]Universities and Colleges Union (WSC037)[bold]Introduction
[normal]This document suggests that a barrier to the careers of women 
[normal]in science in academia is the lack of long term funding leading to a lack of security of employment.
[normal] The prospect of constantly looking for their next funded appointment is daunting to many women especially those trying to combine a career with raising a f
[normal]amily. 
[normal]  In addition that the short term nature of research employment in academia leads to a lack of responsibility being 
[normal]shown by 
[normal]leaders of research for researchers’ career development 
[normal]which is detrimental to
[normal] long term career prospects. It suggests ways
[normal] in which the funding providers could address these issues. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ensuring ar
[normal]rangements 
[normal]for
[normal] the 
[normal]redeployment of staff either within the university or within the existing unit at the end of the pro
[normal]ject 
[normal]Providing bridging between projects – time can be spent writing papers, doing training or writing bids under guidance 
[normal]Appropriate time 
[normal]being 
[normal]given to training and development 
[normal]by timetabling it into activities or proving attendance at appropriate tra
[normal]ining courses 
[normal]– funders need to recognise this need in their funding models
[normal]A statement of how CIs/PIs will demonstrate good practice 
[normal]should also form part of the award process – though without 
[normal]follow up on how this was implemented will be essential
